Thank you. As to not introduce side-effects in other aspects of the site, doing a global `!important` on the `body` is not really something we want to do. In the meantime, I've added the following two methods to the `NavigationMenu.Root`:

```
    onOpenChangeComplete: () => {
      document.body.style.pointerEvents = '';
    }
    onValueChange: () => {
      document.body.style.pointerEvents = '';
    }
```

We can still get the issue to happen, but with these guards in place, we can at least put the mouse cursor back into the submenu and move it out to "unblock" the rest of the site. A more permanent solution would be ideal and any other suggestions you have or might come up with in the future would be much appreciated. Thank you again.

```jsx
  const [value, setValue] = useState<string | null>(null);
  const menuRef = useRef<HTMLElement | null>(null);

  useEffect(() => {
    // Hover events that happen before hydration don't get replayed by React.
    // If the user is already hovering a trigger when hydration completes,
    // open that panel immediately so they don't need to "hover twice".
    const rafId = requestAnimationFrame(() => {
      const rootEl = menuRef.current;
      if (!rootEl) return;

      const hoveredTrigger = rootEl.querySelector<HTMLElement>(
        "[data-nav-value]:hover",
      );
      const nextValue = hoveredTrigger?.dataset.navValue ?? null;
      if (nextValue) setValue(nextValue);
    });

    return () => cancelAnimationFrame(rafId);
  }, []);

  const handleValueChange = (nextValue: unknown) => {
    setValue(typeof nextValue === "string" ? nextValue : null);
  };

...

  <NavigationMenu.Root
        ref={menuRef}
        delay={50}
        closeDelay={50}
        value={debugValue ?? value}
        onValueChange={debugValue ? () => {} : handleValueChange}
```

@atomiks I have possible fix: https://github.com/mui/base-ui/pull/3586

however it has an issue that the workaround didn't have, where the initial position of the panel on the hover during hydration seems to initiate in the wrong place, see video:

![Image](https://github.com/user-attachments/assets/9223561f-e4f9-4c2c-af74-0986bb008721)

It looks like we need to update the doc and consider this a breaking change for the release as well

In the example, adding `max-height` to `.Content` fixes it (and ensuring `border-box` is used):
```css
.Content {
  box-sizing: border-box;
  max-height: var(--available-height);
}
```

I forget our examples need `box-sizing: border-box` when being added to Stackblitz; usually it's part of the CSS reset (really wish it was CSS's default, too...)
